[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "An abstraction is a model or representation that omits some details so that it can focus on other details.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An abstraction is a model or representation that omits some details so that it can focus on other details.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Different abstractions, built for different purposes, omit different kinds of details, and the nature of the abstraction depends on why we are building the model: what information we want to communicate or what analysis we want to perform.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The definition is vague about which details are left out of a model, because different abstractions, built for different purposes, omit different kinds of details.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The key to writing good abstractions is determining, for a particular model, which details are extraneous and can therefore be ignored. The nature of the abstraction depends on why we are building the model in the first place: what information we want to communicate, or what analysis we want to perform.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "An example of abstraction is a decomposition hierarchy, where the system is divided into subsystems and sub-subsystems, with higher levels providing an overview and hiding details, while lower levels reveal more detail about each software unit.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Figure 5.5 was an example of a decomposition hierarchy: a frequently used form of abstraction in which the system is divided into subsystems, which in turn are divided into sub-subsystems, and so on. The top level of the decomposition provides a system-level overview of the solution, hiding details that might otherwise distract us from the design functions and features we want to study and understand. As we move to lower levels of abstraction, we find more detail about each software unit, in terms of its major elements and the relations among those elements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Another example is the interface specification abstraction, which focuses on an element's external behaviors and avoids reference to its internal design details.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each element is described by an interface specification, another type of abstraction that focuses on the element's external behaviors and avoids any reference to the element's internal design details; those details are revealed in models at the next level of decomposition.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A fourth type of abstraction is the virtual machine in a layered architecture, where each layer abstracts away the details of the lower-level layers and presents only its services to the next layer.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A fourth type of abstraction is the virtual machine, such as that in a layered architecture. Each layer i in the architecture uses the services provided by the layer i-1 below it, to create more powerful and reliable services, which it then offers to the layer i+1 above it. ... As such, layer i is a virtual machine that abstracts away the details of the lower-level layers and presents only its services to the next layer.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

