[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Incremental development builds up a system by partitioning it into subsystems based on functionality and then developing these subsystems one at a time in increments.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In incremental development, the system as specified in the requirements documents is partitioned into subsystems by functionality. The releases are defined by beginning with one small,functional subsystem and then adding functionality with each new release.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Each completed unit is a correct implementation of part of the system, making each increment easier to test and correct.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each completed unit is a correct implementation of part of our system. Each increment is easier to test and correct because faults are more likely to be found in the new code, not in the called units that have already been tested and deemed correct.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This approach allows having a working version of a system subset to demonstrate to customers and maintains high morale among developers due to visible progress.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In addition, we always have a working version of a system subset to demonstrate to our customer. Moreover, morale among developers is high, because they frequently make visible progress on the system (Brooks 1995).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Incremental development uses the system's uses relation to devise a schedule, starting from software units that do not depend on others and progressively adding units that depend on previously developed units.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Given a design consisting of software units and their interfaces, we can use the information about the units' dependencies to devise an incremental schedule of development. We start by mapping out the units' uses relation (Parnas 1978b), which relates each software unit to the other software units on which it depends.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Such a uses graph can help us to identify progressively larger subsets of our system that we can implement and test incrementally.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The system is incrementally developed one software unit at a time, where each subtree in the uses graph represents a subset of the system that can be implemented and tested.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The best uses graph has a tree structure or is a forest of tree structures. In such a structure, every subtree is a subset of our system, so we can incrementally develop our system one software unit at a time.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Iterative development delivers a full system at the very beginning and then changes the functionality of each subsystem with each new release.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "However, iterative development delivers a full system at the very beginning and then changes the functionality of each subsystem with each new release.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, primitive forms of all types of functionality are provided in the first release, and subsequent releases improve the quality and usability of these functions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "using iterative development, we would provide primitive forms of all three types of functionality in Release 1. For example, we can create text and then cut and paste it, but the cutting and pasting functions might be clumsy or slow. So in the next iteration, Release 2, we have the same functionality, but have enhanced the quality; now cutting and pasting are easy and quick.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

