[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Risk exposure is quantified by estimating two key aspects of the risk: the risk impact and the risk probability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The risk exposure is computed from the risk impact and the risk probability, so we must estimate each of these risk aspects.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The risk probability is the likelihood that the unwanted event will occur, measured from 0 (impossible) to 1 (certainty).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The likelihood that the event will occur. We must have some idea of the probability that the event will occur... The likelihood of the risk, measured from 0 (impossible) to 1 (certainty) is called the risk probability.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The risk impact is the loss associated with the unwanted outcome, such as financial loss or other negative consequences.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For each possible outcome, we estimate two quantities: the probability of an unwanted outcome, P(UO), and the loss associated with the unwanted outcome, L(UO).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Risk exposure is calculated by multiplying the risk probability by the risk impact.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can quantify the effects of the risks we identify by multiplying the risk impact by the risk probability, to yield the risk exposure.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, if the likelihood that the requirements will change after design is 0.3, and the cost to redesign to new requirements is $50,000, then the risk exposure is $15,000.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, if the likelihood that the requirements will change after design is 0.3, and the cost to redesign to new requirements is $50,000, then the risk exposure is $15,000.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "An example decision tree analysis shows how to estimate risk exposure for different outcomes by multiplying the probability of each unwanted outcome by its associated loss and summing these products.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For each possible outcome, we estimate two quantities: the probability of an unwanted outcome, P(UO), and the loss associated with the unwanted outcome... As the figure illustrates, we have estimated the probability of the first case to be 0.75, of the second to be 0.05, and of the third to be 0.20. The loss associated with an unwanted outcome is estimated to be $500,000 if a critical fault is found, so that the risk exposure is $375,000.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_1090_1092_269"
            }
        ]
    }
]

