[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The chronological relationship between errors, faults, and failures described in Chapter 1 follows a forward direction, where errors lead to faults, which then cause failures.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We learned earlier about the importance of fault identification, correction, and tolerance in creating reliable and robust designs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the analytical direction used when constructing a fault-tree analysis in Chapter 5 is backward, tracing from the failure (effect) back to the possible faults (causes).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We build fault trees that trace backwards through a design, along the logical path from effect to cause.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, while the chronological relationship moves forward from error to failure, fault-tree analysis moves backward from failure to fault to identify and analyze possible causes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We build fault trees that trace backwards through a design, along the logical path from effect to cause.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The traditional Waterfall process model involves a sequential approach where requirements are typically documented upfront during the requirements analysis phase, and changes late in the development cycle are difficult to accommodate.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_538_538_136"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, Extreme Programming (XP) forgoes traditional requirements documentation and instead encodes requirements as test cases that the implementation must pass, emphasizing flexibility and adaptation to current requirements only.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "XP forgoes traditional requirements documentation, and instead encodes the requirements as test cases that the eventual implementation must pass.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "XP handles changing requirements by designing only to current requirements and using refactoring to revisit and reformulate requirements and design to match new and existing needs, often in small steps supported by unit tests and pair programming.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because a major characteristic of XP philosophy is to design only to current requirements, it is often the case that new requirements force the developers to reconsider their existing design. Refactoring refers to revisiting the requirements and design, reformulating them to match new and existing needs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, the trade-off for XP's flexibility is the difficulty of making changes as requirements are added, deleted, or changed, and poorly written test cases can lead to misunderstandings.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Berry (2002a) points out that the trade-off for agile methods' flexibility is the difficulty of making changes to the system as requirements are added, deleted, or changed. But there can be additional problems: XP uses test cases to specify requirements, so a poorly written test case can lead to the kinds of misunderstandings described in this chapter.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In the Application Point approach of COCOMO II Stage 1, the complexity weight of a screen is determined by the number of data tables and views it requires.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For each screen or report, we use the guidance in Table 3.10 and an estimate of the number of data tables needed to produce a description of the screen or report. For example,the booking screen may require the use of three data tables...Thus, the number of data tables is fewer than four, so we must decide whether we need more than eight views. Since we are likely to need fewer than eight views, we rate the booking screen as 'simple' according to the application point table.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "If the number of data tables is fewer than four and the number of views is fewer than eight, the screen is rated as 'simple'; otherwise, it may be rated as 'medium' or 'difficult'.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, the number of data tables is fewer than four, so we must decide whether we need more than eight views. Since we are likely to need fewer than eight views, we rate the booking screen as 'simple' according to the application point table.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The complexity rating (simple, medium, difficult) is then assigned a complexity weight from Table 3.11, where simple screens have a weight of 1, medium screens 2, and medium reports 5.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Next, we use Table 3.11 to assign a complexity rate of 1 to simple screens, 2 to medium screens, and 5 to medium reports; a summary of our ratings is shown in Table 3.15.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "|    | ElementType   | Simple   | Medium   |   Difficult |\n|---:|:--------------|:---------|:---------|------------:|\n|  0 | Screen        | 1        | 2        |           3 |\n|  1 | Report        | 2        | 5        |           8 |",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "After assigning weights to all screens and reports, the weights are summed to obtain the number of new application points (NOP).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We add all the weights in the rightmost column to generate a count of new application points (NOPS): 9.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This NOP value is then divided by a productivity rate to estimate the effort in person-months.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Suppose our developers have low experience and low CASE maturity. Table 3.12 tells us that the productivity rate for this circumstance is 7. Then the COCOMO model tells us that the estimated effort to build the Piccadilly system is NOP divided by the productivity rate, or 1.29 person-months.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The productivity rate is an adjustment factor based on developer experience and capability, coupled with CASE maturity and capability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To use this number for effort estimation, you use an adjustment factor, called a productivity rate, based on developer experience and capability, coupled with CASE maturity and capability.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "For example, if both developer experience and CASE maturity are low, the productivity factor is 7; if developer experience is low but CASE maturity is high, the productivity estimate is the mean of the two values.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, if the developer experience and capability are rated low, and the CASE maturity and capability are rated low, then Table 3.12 tells us that the productivity factor is 7... When the developers' experience is low but CASE maturity is high, the productivity estimate is the mean of the two values: 16.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In a Pipe-and-Filter architecture, data is passed sequentially through a series of independent data-transforming components called filters, connected by pipes that transmit data without modification.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "system functionality is achieved by passing input data through a sequence of data-transforming components, called filters , to produce output data. Pipes are connectors that simply transmit data from one filter to  the  next  without  modifying  the  data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Each filter operates independently and transforms the data before passing it on, with no assumptions about other filters.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each  filter  is  an  independent  function  that makes no assumptions about other filters that may be applied to the data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Data flows continuously from one filter to the next, being transformed along the way, and is not stored persistently within the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "a data item is no longer stored in any location, but rather flows from one filter to another, being transformed along the way.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, a Blackboard repository architecture centralizes the system's key data in a shared data store, called the blackboard, which is managed centrally.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An important property of this style of architecture is the centralized management of the system's key data.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the data store, we can localize responsibility for storing persistent data, managing concurrent access to the data, enforcing security and privacy policies, and protecting the data against faults (e.g., via backups).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The blackboard acts as a shared repository where multiple knowledge sources read and write data, enabling coordination and integration of their contributions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Typical blackboard.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_2026_2027_496"
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This centralized data storage supports persistent data management, concurrent access control, and security enforcement, unlike the transient data flow in Pipe-and-Filter.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the data store, we can localize responsibility for storing persistent data, managing concurrent access to the data, enforcing security and privacy policies, and protecting the data against faults (e.g., via backups).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "According to the V model, the left side of the V represents the analysis and design phases, while the right side represents the corresponding testing and maintenance phases.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "coding forms the point of the V, with analysis and design on the left, testing and maintenance on the right.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Verification activities on the right side of the V map to ensuring that the design and code conform to the specifications and requirements defined on the left side.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The V model suggests that unit and integration testing can also be used to verify the program design. That is, during unit and integration testing, the coders and test team members should ensure that all aspects of the program design have been implemented correctly in the code. Similarly, system testing should verify the system design, making sure that all system design aspects are correctly implemented.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Validation activities ensure that the requirements are correctly implemented and meet the customer's needs, which is done through acceptance testing on the right side of the V.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Acceptance testing, which is conducted by the customer rather than the developer, validates the requirements by associating a testing step with each element of the specification; this type of testing checks to see that all requirements have been fully implemented before the system is accepted and paid for.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, unit and integration testing verify the program design, system testing verifies the system design, and acceptance testing validates the requirements, linking the testing phases on the right side of the V to the corresponding analysis and design phases on the left.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The V model suggests that unit and integration testing can also be used to verify the program design... Similarly, system testing should verify the system design... Acceptance testing... validates the requirements by associating a testing step with each element of the specification.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Verification ensures that the system is built correctly according to the design and requirements, while validation ensures that the right system is built to meet stakeholder needs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In verification , we check that one document or artifact conforms to another. Thus, we verify that our code conforms to our design, and that our design conforms to our requirements specification; at the requirements level, we verify that our requirements specification conforms to the requirements definition. To summarize, verification ensures that we build the system right , whereas validation ensures that we build the right system!",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "If problems are found during verification and validation on the right side, the corresponding phases on the left side of the V can be reexecuted to fix and improve requirements, design, and code before retesting.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The model's linkage of the left side with the right side of the V implies that if problems are found during verification and validation, then the left side of the V can be reexecuted to fix and improve the requirements, design, and code before the testing steps on the right side are reenacted.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A Chief Programmer team might be a poor organizational choice if the majority of the team members are \"Rational Introverts\" because the chief programmer team requires the chief to make decisions quickly and be an extrovert, while most communication is between the chief and individual members rather than among team members themselves.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Clearly, the chief programmer must be good at making decisions quickly, so the chief is likely to be an extrovert. However, if most of the team members are introverts, the chief programmer team may not be the best structure for the project.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The organization of the chief programmer team is illustrated in Figure 3.11. By placing all responsibility for all decisions with the chief programmer, the team structure minimizes the amount of communication needed during the project. Each team member must communicate often with the chief, but not necessarily with other team members.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_940_940_229"
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "FIGURE 3.10 Work styles ... Rational INTROVERT: Asks others, Decides logically",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_923_923_224"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Chief Programmer team structure is hierarchical and suited for projects with high certainty, stability, and repetition, where little communication among members is needed.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A National Science Foundation (1983) investigation found that projects with a high degree of certainty, stability, uniformity, and repetition can be accomplished more effectively by a hierarchical organizational structure such as the chief programmer team. These projects require little communication among project members, so they are well-suited to an organization that stresses rules, specialization, formality, and a clear definition of organizational hierarchy.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For projects with high uncertainty, a more democratic and loosely structured team organization is recommended, where participation in decision making is encouraged and open communication is promoted.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the other hand, when there is much uncertainty involved in a project, a more democratic approach may be better. For example, if the requirements may change as development proceeds, the project has a degree of uncertainty. ... Here, participation in decision making, a loosely defined hierarchy, and the encouragement of open communication can be effective.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "An alternative team structure to the Chief Programmer team for such uncertain projects is the egoless team structure, which is democratic and holds everyone equally responsible, with decisions made by voting and criticism directed at the product rather than individuals.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An alternative is based on the idea of 'egoless' programming, as described by Weinberg (1971). Instead of a single point of responsibility, an egoless approach holds everyone equally responsible. Moreover, the process is separated from the individuals; criticism is made of the product or the result, not the people involved. The egoless team structure is democratic, and all team members vote on a decision, whether it concerns design considerations or testing techniques.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Object Constraint Language (OCL) supplements a standard UML class diagram by allowing the expression of precise constraints such as invariants on the model elements, which are not easily represented in UML diagrams alone.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "OCL can augment many of UML's models. For example, it can be used to express invariants, preconditions, and post-conditions in class diagrams",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To enforce that no two publications can share the same call number, an OCL invariant is written on the Publication class specifying that for any two distinct instances of Publication, their call numbers must be different.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The topmost constraint is an invariant on the Publication class, and specifies that call numbers are unique. Thus, the constraint literally says that for any two publications, p1 and p2, returned by allinstances, if p1 and p2 are not the same publication, then they have different call numbers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The specific OCL navigational constructs used to express this invariant include the allinstances construct, which returns all instances of the Publication class, and the forall construct, which applies a condition to all pairs of publications. The implies connective is used to state that if two publications are different, then their call numbers must differ.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Construct allinstances, which returns all instances of the Publication class; Constructs forall, and, and implies, which correspond to the first-order connectives described above",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The topmost constraint is an invariant on the Publication class, and specifies that call numbers are unique. Thus, the constraint literally says that for any two publications, p1 and p2, returned by allinstances, if p1 and p2 are not the same publication, then they have different call numbers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The textbook argues that high-level Petri nets are better suited than state-machine models for representing processes like an emergency room triage because Petri nets can model concurrency and synchronization of events whose order of occurrence is not important.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "These features of concurrency and synchronization are especially useful for modeling events whose order of occurrence is not important. Consider the emergency room in a hospital. Before a patient can be treated, several events must occur... The events occur in no particular order, but all must occur before a team of doctors begins a more thorough examination.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "A state-machine model might specify only a single order of events, excluding acceptable behaviors, or specify all possible sequences, resulting in an overly complex model.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A state-machine model of the emergency room might specify only a single order of events, thereby excluding several acceptable behaviors, or it might specify all possible sequences of events, resulting in an overly complex model for a relatively simple problem.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "In contrast, a Petri net model nicely avoids both problems by allowing concurrent activities and synchronization without constraining the order of events.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A Petri net model of the same emergency room nicely avoids both of these problems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A delay in an activity that has zero slack time pushes all subsequent activities on that path forward, causing them to be late as well if there is no slack to absorb the delay.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Notice what happens when an activity on the critical path begins late (i.e., later than its earliest start time). The late start pushes all subsequent critical path activities forward, forcing them to be late, too, if there is no slack.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This cascading delay logically increases the projected staff-days on a resource histogram because the delayed activities and their dependent activities require resources for a longer period than initially planned.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Critical path analysis of a project schedule tells us who must wait for what as the project is being developed. It also tells us which activities must be completed on schedule to avoid delay.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The specific term for the path that contains these zero-slack activities is the critical path.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Since the critical path has no slack, there is no margin for error when performing the activities along its route.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The U.S. government defines Return on Investment (ROI) in terms of dollars, focusing on reducing operating costs, predicting dollar savings, and calculating the cost of employing new technologies.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The government views ROI in terms of dollars,looking at reducing operating costs,predicting dollar savings,and calculating the cost of employing new technologies.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "In contrast, industry defines ROI in terms of effort, emphasizing saving time or using fewer people, and includes factors such as training, schedule, risk, quality, productivity, process, customer, costs, and business.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the other hand, industry viewed investment in terms of effort, rather than cost or dollars. That is, companies were interested in saving time or using fewer people, and their definition of return on investment reflected this focus on decreasing effort.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- training - schedule - risk - quality - productivity - process - customer - costs - business",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The payback period in a cost-benefit analysis is mathematically calculated as the length of time before accumulated benefits recover the costs of implementation, which is the cost divided by the benefits.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Another useful measure is the payback period : the length of time before accumulated benefits recover the costs of implementation.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "For example, the payback period for restructuring a software module is calculated as $300,000 divided by $280,000, resulting in approximately 1.07 years or 13 months.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In our example, the payback period for restructuring the sorted-index module (design 2) is $300,000/$280,000 = 1.07 of a year = approximately 13 months",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The primary development goal of building a throwaway rapid prototype during the requirements elicitation phase is to quickly answer questions about the problem or proposed solution without intending the prototype to be part of the final delivered software.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A throwaway prototype is software that is developed to learn more about a problem or about a proposed solution, and that is never intended to be part of the delivered software.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, during the software architecture design phase, a throwaway prototype is developed primarily to explore design issues and assess feasibility or particular characteristics of a proposed design, with the prototype often discarded after learning from it.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If a prototype is intended only to explore design issues, we may not give its development the same careful attention that we would give to a real system. For this reason, we frequently discard the prototype and build the actual system from scratch, rather than try to salvage parts from the prototype.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, the requirements phase prototype focuses on understanding and clarifying requirements quickly, while the architecture phase prototype focuses on evaluating design feasibility and characteristics, often with less emphasis on quality and more on learning design aspects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A throwaway prototype is software that is developed to learn more about a problem or about a proposed solution, and that is never intended to be part of the delivered software.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If a prototype is intended only to explore design issues, we may not give its development the same careful attention that we would give to a real system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The representation of conditions and states in a Parnas Table for calculating a library due date is structured as a tabular format where rows and columns define predicates or input conditions, and the internal table entries specify the function results or output values for each case.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The rows and columns define Calc due date , an operation in our library example.The information is represented as a Normal Table, which is a type of Parnas table.The column and row headers are predicates used to specify cases, and the internal table entries store the possible function results.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Each internal table entry represents a distinct case in the function's definition, and the table covers all possible combinations of conditions affecting the calculation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, each internal table entry represents a distinct case in the function's definition. ... Notice how the column and row headers are structured to cover all possible combinations of conditions that can affect the calculation of a loaned item's due date.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the pre-conditions and post-conditions in a formal Z specification schema for a \"Return\" operation are expressed as logical predicates and state updates that specify the conditions before and after the operation, including variable values and state modifications.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The top section of an operation schema indicates whether the operation modifies ( D ) or simply queries ( X ) the system state, and identifies the inputs (?) and outputs (!) of the operation. The bottom section of an operation schema specifies the operation's pre-conditions and post-conditions. In operations that modify the system state, unprimed variables represent variable values before the operation is performed, and primed variables represent values following the operation.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The post-conditions describe updates to system variables and conditions that must hold after the operation, often using symbolic notation to represent state changes and function mappings.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The post-conditions update the Catalogue to include the new Item , and specify that the other library variables do not change value ... The post-conditions remove the returned item from variables Borrowers and DueDates ; these updates use Z symbol y , 'domain subtraction,' ... The next two post-conditions are updates to variable Fines , conditioned on whether the Patron incurs an overdue fine ... These updates use symbol å , which 'maps' a domain value 'to' a range value, and symbol ± which 'overrides' a function mapping ... The last two post-conditions specify that the values of variables Catalogue and OnReserve do not change.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Structurally, the Parnas Table organizes conditions and results in a matrix form that localizes each output variable's definition in a distinct table, facilitating case-by-case review, while the Z schema uses a formal logical notation to specify state changes and constraints before and after an operation in a more declarative manner.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A functional specification expressed using Parnas tables is best decomposed into a single function per output variable. For every input event and for every condition on entities or other variables, each function specifies the value of its corresponding output variable. The advantage of this model structure over a state-machine model is that the definition of each output variable is localized in a distinct table, rather than spread throughout the model as actions on state transitions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The \"hot standby\" redundancy fault-recovery tactic failed during the Ariane-5 maiden flight because it was designed under the assumption that hardware and software failures behave similarly, which is not the case.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Ariane-5 included a number of redundant components in which both the hardware equipment and the associated software were identical. In most cases, one of the components was supposed to be active; the other was to stay in 'hot standby' mode, ready to become the active component if the current active component failed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The textbook explains that hardware failures are independent, meaning if one hardware unit fails, the standby unit is usually unaffected and can take over as the active unit. However, software failures tend to be logical errors that affect all copies of a software component simultaneously, especially when processing the same input.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Hardware failures are independent: if one unit fails, the standby unit is usually unaffected and can take over as the active unit. By contrast, software faults tend to be logical errors, so all copies of a software component have the same set of faults. Moreover, even if the software is not the underlying cause of a failure, replicated software components are likely to exhibit the same bad behavior in response to bad input.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, the hot standby redundancy in Ariane-5 was likely to recover only from hardware failures and not from software failures, which was the actual cause of the failure during the flight.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For these reasons, the hot standby redundancy in Ariane-5 is likely to recover only from hardware failures.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This was demonstrated in the Ariane-5 failure where both inertial reference systems (SRIs) suffered the same overflow error simultaneously, causing both to shut down and leading to the failure.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "This was the situation with the failed inertial reference systems (SRIs) on the Ariane-5: both units suffered the same overflow error, simultaneously.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A 'pure' layered system organizes software units into layers where each layer provides services to the layer above and acts as a client to the layer below, accessing only the services of the immediately lower layer.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In a 'pure' layered system, a software unit in a given layer can access only the other units in the same layer and services offered by the interface to the layer immediately below it.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This strict layering enforces explicit interfaces between layers, which helps to hide the internal details of each layer and restricts interactions to well-defined access points.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "each layer raises the level of abstraction of the communication services that are available to the next layer, and hides all of the details about how those services are implemented.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "By limiting access to adjacent layers and using explicit interfaces, the system reduces coupling between layers, which minimizes the likelihood that changes in one layer will ripple to other layers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "because a layer can interact only with its neighboring layers, layer modification is relatively easy; such changes should affect at most only the two adjacent layers.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A software unit's interface reveals the unit's public requisites and responsibilities, and hides the unit's private design decisions. If a unit interacts with other units only through their interfaces (e.g., calling public access methods), then changes to one unit will not spread beyond the unit's boundary unless its interface changes",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, the tactics of reducing coupling and using explicit interfaces are realized in a pure layered architecture by restricting layer interactions to adjacent layers through well-defined interfaces, which confines the impact of modifications to at most two layers and preserves maintainability and portability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In general, the layering style is useful whenever we can decompose our system's functionality into steps, each of which builds on previous steps. The resulting design is easier to port to other platforms, if the lowest level encapsulates the software's interactions with the platform. Moreover, because a layer can interact only with its neighboring layers, layer modification is relatively easy; such changes should affect at most only the two adjacent layers.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A software unit's interface reveals the unit's public requisites and responsibilities, and hides the unit's private design decisions. If a unit interacts with other units only through their interfaces (e.g., calling public access methods), then changes to one unit will not spread beyond the unit's boundary unless its interface changes",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In the COCOMO II model, the transition from Stage 1 (Application Composition) to Stage 3 (Postarchitecture) involves a change in the metrics used to measure system size and the types of cost drivers applied to the effort estimate.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "At stage 1, application points supply the size measure. ... At stage 3, the postarchitecture stage, development has begun, and far more information is known. In this stage, sizing can be done in terms of function points or lines of code, and many cost factors can be estimated with some degree of comfort.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Stage 1 uses application points as the size measure, which counts elements like screens, reports, and third-generation language components classified by complexity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "At stage 1, application points supply the size measure. This size measure is an extension of the object-point approach ... To compute application points, you first count the number of screens, reports, and third-generation language components ... Next, you classify each application element as simple, medium, or difficult.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "By Stage 3, sizing is done in terms of function points or lines of code, reflecting more detailed knowledge of the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By stage 3, the postarchitecture stage, development has begun, and far more information is known. In this stage, sizing can be done in terms of function points or lines of code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The types of cost drivers also change; Stage 1 uses a smaller set of cost drivers related to high-level effort generators, while Stage 3 includes many cost factors to adjust the initial effort estimate, including models of reuse, maintenance, and breakage.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "COCOMO II also includes models of reuse, takes into account maintenance and breakage ... and more. As with the original COCOMO, the model includes cost factors to adjust the initial effort estimate.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Notice that stage 2 of COCOMO II is intended for use during the early stages of design. The set of cost drivers in this stage is smaller than the set used in stage 3, reflecting lesser understanding of the project's parameters at stage 2.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "According to McCall's quality model, Usability is linked to internal criteria such as Operability and Training.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_188_188_57"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Developers can use fit criteria to transform subjective quality requirements like Usability into objectively testable specifications by quantifying the extent to which the requirement must be met.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Robertson and Robertson (1999) point out that testability (which they call 'measurability') can be addressed when requirements are being elicited. The idea is to quantify the extent to which each requirement must be met.These fit criteria form objective standards for judging whether a proposed solution satisfies the requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, subjective quality requirements like Usability can be evaluated using metrics or focus groups, such as: 75% of users shall judge the new system to be as usable as the existing system, or after training, 90% of users shall be able to process a new account within 5 minutes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "It is relatively easy to determine fit criteria for quality requirements that are naturally quantitative (e.g., performance, size, precision, accuracy, time to delivery). What about more subjective quality requirements, like usability or maintainability? In these cases, developers use focus groups or metrics to evaluate fit criteria: - 75% of users shall judge the new system to be as usable as the existing system. - After training, 90% of users shall be able to process a new account within 5 minutes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This approach ensures that the evaluation of Usability is objective and measurable, rather than subjective and ambiguous.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By this, he means that once a requirement is stated, we should be able to determine whether or not a proposed solution meets the requirement. This evaluation must be objective; that is, the conclusion as to whether the requirement is satisfied must not vary according to who is doing the evaluation.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The initial risk exposure is calculated by multiplying the risk probability by the potential loss impact. Given a risk probability of 0.25 and a loss impact of $500,000, the initial risk exposure is 0.25 × $500,000 = $125,000.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can quantify the effects of the risks we identify by multiplying the risk impact by the risk probability, to yield the risk exposure . For example, if the likelihood that the requirements will change after design is 0.3, and the cost to redesign to new requirements is $50,000, then the risk exposure is $15,000.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To determine the risk reduction leverage, the project manager must calculate the difference between the risk exposure before and after risk reduction, then divide this difference by the cost of reducing the risk.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To aid decision making about risk reduction, we must take into account the cost of reducing the risk. We call risk leverage the difference in risk exposure divided by the cost of reducing the risk.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "/ 1 cost of risk reduction 2 1 Risk exposure before reduction -risk exposure after reduction 2",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, the formula for risk reduction leverage is (Risk exposure before reduction - Risk exposure after reduction) / Cost of risk reduction. The project manager needs to estimate the risk exposure after reduction to complete this calculation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "risk reduction leverage is If the leverage value is not high enough to justify the action, then we can look for other less costly or more effective reduction techniques.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A Message Sequence Chart (MSC) visually depicts the passage of time by showing message arrows that may slope downwards to reflect the time between when a message is sent and when it is received.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A message arrow may slope downwards (e.g., message recall notice ) to reflect the passage of time between when the message is sent and when it is received.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "It depicts the creation of new entities with a dashed arrow representing a create event that spawns a new entity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "a dashed arrow, optionally annotated with data parameters, represents a create event that spawns a new entity",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, a UML Statechart diagram depicts the local variables and internal activities of a single entity by showing how a class's instances change state and how their attributes change value as the objects interact with each other.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A UML statechart diagram depicts the dynamic behavior of the objects in a UML class. ... A statechart diagram shows how a class's instances should change state and how their attributes should change value as the objects interact with each other.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Statechart diagrams show the internal behavior of a single entity, including state hierarchy, concurrency, and intermachine communication, whereas MSCs show the events that pass between entities without detailing each entity's behavior.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An MSC shows the events that pass between entities without saying much about each entity's behavior, whereas a statechart diagram shows how a single entity reacts to input events and generates output events.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "UML statechart diagrams have a rich syntax, much of it borrowed from Harel's original conception of statecharts (Harel 1987), including state hierarchy, concurrency, and intermachine communication.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "According to Abdel-Hamid's system dynamics model of software development, increasing the staff size to alleviate schedule pressure inadvertently impacts the average nominal potential productivity and communication overhead in a causal manner.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Schedule pressures affect this fraction, as do the developers' tolerances for workload. Staff size affects productivity, too, but the more staff, the more likely it is that time will be needed just to communicate information among team members.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_650_652_167"
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Similarly, the larger the staff (reflected in staff size), the more time is devoted to communication among project members (communication overhead).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Specifically, while increasing staff size may reduce schedule pressure by adding more resources, it also increases communication overhead because more staff members require more time to coordinate and share information.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Staff size affects productivity, too, but the more staff, the more likely it is that time will be needed just to communicate information among team members.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_650_652_167"
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Similarly, the larger the staff (reflected in staff size), the more time is devoted to communication among project members (communication overhead).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This increased communication overhead reduces the fraction of each day that developers can devote to productive work, thereby lowering the average nominal potential productivity despite the larger staff size.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Schedule pressures affect this fraction, as do the developers' tolerances for workload. Staff size affects productivity, too, but the more staff, the more likely it is that time will be needed just to communicate information among team members.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_650_652_167"
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A company justifies the initial higher development costs of creating a core asset base for a software product line through strategic business planning and forecasting market trends to identify a family of products with enough commonality to warrant a product-line approach.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "First, we employ strategic business planning to identify the family of products we want to build.We use knowledge and good judgment to forecast market trends and predict the demand for various products. Second, we scope our plans, so that we focus on products that have enough in common to warrant a product-line approach to development.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The company plans upfront to manufacture and market several related products that share assets and resources, which leads to economies of scope and reduces the total cost and effort compared to developing products individually.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The corporate strategy for designing and developing the related products is based on the reuse of elements of a common product line . The company plans upfront to manufacture and market several related products. Part of the planning process involves deciding how those products will share assets and resources... As a result, the cost and effort to develop the family of products is far less than the sum of the costs to develop the products individually.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Scoping product commonality is a challenging problem that affects the return on investment: striving for high commonality may exclude profitable products, while including loosely related products reduces commonality and savings.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Product-line scoping is a challenging problem. If we strive for some notion of optimal commonality among the products (e.g.,by insisting on reusing 80 percent of the code), we may exclude some interesting and profitable products that lie outside of the scope. On the other hand, if we try to include any product that looks related, we reduce the degree of commonality among the derived products, and consequently the amount of savings that can be achieved.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A successful product line balances these extremes with a core architecture that supports the most promising products, ensuring that each derived product incorporates a significant fraction of software units from the core asset base, which improves productivity and return on investment.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A successful product line lies somewhere in the middle of these two extremes, with a core architecture that strongly supports the more promising products that we want to build. In the end, a product line's success depends on both its inherent variability and the degree of overlap between its core asset base and the derived products. To obtain desired productivity-improvement numbers, each derived product's architecture must start with the product-line architecture, incorporating a significant fraction of its software units from the product line's core asset base.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The less a derived product has in common with the product line, the more its development resembles a completely new product, which reduces the benefits and return on investment from the product line approach.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The less the final derived product has in common with the product line, the more the derived product's development will resemble a completely new (i.e., nonderived) product.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The role of the \"Transformed Specification\" in the operational specification process model conceptually differs from the transition between a throwaway prototype and an evolutionary prototype in that the transformed specification involves enacting the system requirements in an executable form to demonstrate and assess system behavior early in development, merging functionality and design.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the operational specification model, the system requirements are evaluated or executed in a way that demonstrates the behavior of the system.That is,once the requirements are specified,they can be enacted using a software package, so their implications can be assessed before design begins.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "This type of process is very different from traditional models such as the waterfall model. The waterfall model separates the functionality of the system from the design (i.e., what the system is to do is separated from how the system does it), intending to keep the customer needs apart from the implementation. However,an operational specification allows the functionality and the design to be merged.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the transition between a throwaway prototype and an evolutionary prototype during requirements engineering is about the purpose and fate of the prototype software: a throwaway prototype is developed quickly to explore questions and is discarded, while an evolutionary prototype is developed with care to be incorporated into the final product, requiring it to meet quality standards.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A throwaway prototype is software that is developed to learn more about a problem or about a proposed solution, and that is never intended to be part of the delivered software.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In contrast, an evolutionary prototype is software that is developed not only to help us answer questions but also to be incorporated into the final product. As such, we have to be much more careful in its development, because this software has to eventually exhibit the quality requirements (e.g., response rate, modularity) of the final product, and these qualities cannot be retrofitted.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, while the transformed specification in operational specification is about early executable evaluation of requirements merging design and functionality, the throwaway versus evolutionary prototype distinction is about whether the prototype is discarded or evolved into the final product, reflecting different approaches to handling uncertainty and development focus during requirements engineering.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Data-flow diagrams (DFDs) provide an intuitive model of a system's high-level functionality and data dependencies, focusing on tasks to be completed, functions to be computed, and data to be analyzed, transformed, or recorded.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the strengths of data-flow diagrams is that they provide an intuitive model of a proposed system's high-level functionality and of the data dependencies among the various processes.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For this reason, notations that promote decomposition by functionality have always been popular.\n - Tasks to be completed\n - Functions to be computed\n - Data to be analyzed, transformed, or recorded",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In Stage 1 of the COCOMO II estimation model, Application Points are used as a size measure, which are computed by counting the number of screens, reports, and third-generation language components involved in the application, classified by complexity (simple, medium, difficult).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "At stage 1, projects usually build prototypes to resolve high-risk issues involving user interfaces, software and system interaction, performance, or technological maturity. Here, little is known about the likely size of the final product under consideration, so COCOMO II estimates size in what its creators call application points.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To compute application points, you first count the number of screens, reports, and third-generation language components that will be involved in the application. It is assumed that these elements are defined in a standard way as part of an integrated computer-aided software engineering environment. Next, you classify each application element as simple, medium, or difficult.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The data stores and actors identified in the DFD would influence the complexity weights used to calculate Application Points by determining the number and complexity of the application elements such as screens and reports that represent interactions with these actors and data stores.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the strengths of data-flow diagrams is that they provide an intuitive model of a proposed system's high-level functionality and of the data dependencies among the various processes.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To compute application points, you first count the number of screens, reports, and third-generation language components that will be involved in the application.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, the DFD's identification of data stores and actors helps define the functional elements whose quantity and complexity are key inputs to the Application Points calculation in COCOMO II Stage 1, linking the high-level functional model to the early effort estimation process.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the strengths of data-flow diagrams is that they provide an intuitive model of a proposed system's high-level functionality and of the data dependencies among the various processes.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "At stage 1, projects usually build prototypes to resolve high-risk issues involving user interfaces, software and system interaction, performance, or technological maturity. Here, little is known about the likely size of the final product under consideration, so COCOMO II estimates size in what its creators call application points.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "According to McCall's quality model, Flexibility is a key external quality factor.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_188_188_57"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To achieve this factor by minimizing the number of indirectly affected software units when a change occurs, the architect should apply modifiability tactics that focus on reducing dependencies among software units.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By contrast, tactics for minimizing the impact on indirectly affected software units focus on reducing dependencies among software units.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The specific modifiability tactics to apply to the system's interfaces and coupling are:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Lower coupling among software units to reduce the likelihood that a change to one unit will ripple to other units.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Coupling: As we discuss in detail in Chapter 6,the level of coupling among software units is the degree to which the units depend on each other. By lowering coupling, we reduce the likelihood that a change to one unit will ripple to other units.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Use interfaces that reveal only the unit's public requisites and responsibilities while hiding private design decisions, so changes do not spread beyond the unit's boundary unless the interface itself changes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Interfaces: A software unit's interface reveals the unit's public requisites and responsibilities, and hides the unit's private design decisions. If a unit interacts with other units only through their interfaces (e.g., calling public access methods), then changes to one unit will not spread beyond the unit's boundary unless its interface changes (e.g., if method signatures, preconditions, or postconditions change).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Provide multiple interfaces so that a unit modified to provide new data or services can offer them using a new interface without changing existing interfaces, thus not affecting dependencies on existing interfaces.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Multiple interfaces: A unit modified to provide new data or services can offer them using a new interface to the unit without changing any of the unit's existing interfaces. This way, dependencies on the existing interfaces are unaffected by the change.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Establishing specific fit criteria during the requirements phase makes subjective quality requirements like \"usability\" more testable and measurable.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Robertsons suggest three ways to help make requirements testable: Specify a quantitative description for each adverb and adjective so that the meaning of qualifiers is clear and unambiguous.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This quantification allows for clearer estimation of the probability and impact of risks related to failing to satisfy these quality requirements, which are essential parameters in calculating risk exposure.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The risk exposure is computed from the risk impact and the risk probability, so we must estimate each of these risk aspects.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "With better-defined fit criteria, the parameters used in risk reduction leverage calculations become more precise, enabling more accurate assessment of the cost-effectiveness of risk reduction actions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To aid decision making about risk reduction, we must take into account the cost of reducing the risk. We call risk leverage the difference in risk exposure divided by the cost of reducing the risk.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, making subjective quality requirements testable through specific fit criteria directly influences the estimation of risk exposure and the calculation of risk reduction leverage during project planning.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Interestingly, what gets measured gets done.That is, unless a fit criterion is unrealistic, it will probably be met.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A highly hierarchical Chief Programmer team structure theoretically faces fewer communication bottlenecks because all responsibility for decisions is centralized with the chief programmer, minimizing the amount of communication needed during the project.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By placing all responsibility for all decisions with the chief programmer, the team structure minimizes the amount of communication needed during the project.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Each team member communicates primarily with the chief rather than with other team members, reducing the number of communication paths and potential bottlenecks.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each team member must communicate often with the chief, but not necessarily with other team members.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This contrasts with a loosely structured, egoless team where communication is more distributed and potentially more complex.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "When developing a system specified with a tightly coupled algebraic specification notation like SDL Data, which involves complex, user-defined variable types and synchronous communication within blocks, the need for clear, centralized decision-making and minimized communication overhead is critical.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "SDL data type definitions are used to declare complex, user-defined variable types.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Signal routes pass messages synchronously, so messages sent between processes in the same block are received instantaneously.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The hierarchical structure supports this by ensuring that tightly coupled components and decisions are managed efficiently through a single point of control.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Processes that need to synchronize with one another and that are highly coupled should reside in the same block.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A single-element cut-set (e.g., {A1}) derived from a fault-tree analysis strictly represents that the top failure could be caused by a single event, A1.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, if any member of the cut-set is a singleton event set, {A i }, then the top failure could be caused by a single event, A i .",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "From the internal developer view, this means that the fault tree traces backwards from the observable failure to identify the minimal event combinations that could cause it, and a single-element cut-set indicates a minimal cause that is a single fault event.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Fault-tree analysis ... helps us to examine a design and look for faults that might lead to failure. We build fault trees that trace backwards through a design, along the logical path from effect to cause.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The cut-set represents the set of minimal event combinations that could lead to the failure listed at the top of the cut-set tree.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Lai's process transition diagram represents states as labeled boxes and transitions as labeled arrows connecting these states, showing how states are related to one another in a sequential manner.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Transition diagrams supplement the process model by showing how the states are related to one another. For example, Figure 2.12 illustrates the transitions for a car.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_644_644_165"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, a high-level Petri net model uses places (circles) to represent activities or conditions, transitions (bars) to represent events that change states, and tokens within places to represent enabling conditions for transitions to fire, thus modeling concurrency and synchronization explicitly.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Petri nets (Peterson 1977) are a form of state-transition notation that is used to model concurrent activities and their interactions. The circles in the net are places that represent activities or conditions, and the bars represent transitions. Directed arrows, called arcs, connect a transition with its input places and its output places. The places are populated with tokens, which act as enabling conditions for the transitions. When a transition fires, it removes tokens from each of its input places and inserts tokens into each of its output places.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_1453_1454_356"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Structurally, Lai's diagrams focus on sequential state changes with explicit state nodes and transitions, while Petri nets emphasize the enabling conditions for transitions through token distribution, allowing modeling of concurrent and synchronized activities.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A transition is enabled if each of its input places contains enough tokens to contribute its arc's weight's worth of tokens, should the enabled transition actually fire. Thus, in Figure 4.12, transitions Return, Withdraw Return Request, and Withdraw Loan Request are all enabled; firing transition Return removes a token from each of the places ReturnRequest and OnLoan, and inserts a token into Avail. The net's marking, which is the distribution of tokens among places, changes as transitions fire.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Lai's notation is a good example of how multiple structures and strategies can be used to capture a great deal of information about the software development process.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Modeling the complete system's dynamic behavior using Message Sequence Charts (MSCs) in a pure publish-subscribe architectural style with implicit invocation is inherently difficult or misleading because publish-subscribe systems involve components that interact by broadcasting and reacting to events without knowing about each other.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In a publish-subscribe architecture, components interact by broadcasting and reacting to events. A component expresses interest in an event by subscribing to it. Then, when another component announces ( publishes ) that the event has taken place, the subscribing components are notified. ... publish-subscribe components know nothing about each other. Instead, the publishing component simply announces events and then waits for interested components to react; each subscribing component simply reacts to event announcements, regardless of how they are published.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This lack of direct knowledge and control over which components are subscribed and how they react makes it difficult to capture the exact interactions and sequence of events in MSCs, which are designed to specify key scenarios with clear message exchanges between known entities.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Publish-subscribe systems are difficult to test, because the behavior of a publishing component will depend on which subscribing components are monitoring its events. Thus, we cannot test the component in isolation and infer its correctness in an integrated system.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Message Sequence Charts (ITU 1996) are an enhanced event-trace notation, with facilities for creating and destroying entities, specifying actions and timers, and composing traces.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Message Sequence Charts are usually used only to describe key scenarios rather than to specify entire problems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, MSCs face a trace-explosion problem when trying to specify entire problems, and since publish-subscribe systems can have many possible subscribers reacting in various ways to events, the number of possible interaction traces grows exponentially, making MSCs impractical for complete system modeling.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Such composition and refinement features help to reduce the number of MSCs one would need to write to specify a problem completely. However, these features do not completely address the trace-explosion problem, so Message Sequences Charts are usually used only to describe key scenarios rather than to specify entire problems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In Extreme Programming (XP), future, unanticipated requirements are not planned or designed for; the system is built only to the requirements defined at the time.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Extreme programming (XP) takes agile requirements processes to the extreme, in that the system is built to the requirements that happen to be defined at the time, with no planning or designing for possible future requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "XP focuses on current requirements and encodes them as test cases, foregoing traditional requirements documentation and emphasizing flexibility over anticipating future needs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Moreover, XP forgoes traditional requirements documentation, and instead encodes the requirements as test cases that the eventual implementation must pass.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Simple design: Design is kept simple by addressing only current needs.This approach reflects the philosophy that anticipating future needs can lead to unnecessary functionality.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, when scoping and designing a core asset base for a Software Product Line architecture, the approach is strategic and involves planning for variability and future reuse across multiple products, which requires anticipating and managing future, unanticipated requirements.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The software industry's definition of Return on Investment (ROI) primarily focuses on effort reduction and time savings, emphasizing saving time or using fewer people as key benefits.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the other hand, industry viewed investment in terms of effort, rather than cost or dollars. That is, companies were interested in saving time or using fewer people, and their definition of return on investment reflected this focus on decreasing effort.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the mathematical calculation of a design's payback period in a formal cost-benefit analysis is a financial measure that calculates the length of time before accumulated monetary benefits recover the costs of implementation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Another useful measure is the payback period : the length of time before accumulated benefits recover the costs of implementation.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, while the software industry's ROI definition is effort- and time-based, focusing on operational improvements, the payback period is a financial metric expressed in monetary terms, reflecting the time to recoup investment costs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The government views ROI in terms of dollars, looking at reducing operating costs, predicting dollar savings, and calculating the cost of employing new technologies. On the other hand, industry viewed investment in terms of effort, rather than cost or dollars.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In general, an ROI of 1 or greater means that the design's benefits outweigh its costs. The higher the ROI value, the more effective the design. Another useful measure is the payback period : the length of time before accumulated benefits recover the costs of implementation.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    }
]
